Since Art was impressed with Much Too Fast country boy wannabe big chief Ed and Ed was impressed with Smart, nice, good looking and very important dude, Art, (MTF, told me, he was impressed with you and I think he was blushing at the time). And MTF buttering up Mom, lavishing all kinds of nice words on account he want to be moms favorite and so that he can stay out late, I though it would be appropriate for us to honor one of our own<br><br>
There were Marines I served with in Nam, that I didn’t care for because they sought out ways to avoid their duty, some had been drafted and things started to change, it was no longer the Corps I had joined. Demonstrations against the war back at home didn’t help matters and we began to loose something in the overall process. The honor, pride and luster became tinted.  <br><br>
To volunteer to serve in an unpopular war and not be ashamed about it afterwards means a lot to me and it is in the highest tradition and reflection of those I served with in Nam. Individual like the roll call of those I admire and respect as I posted in the tread above.  <br><br>
To me, courage, honor, service, dignity and friendship meant and has meant a lot.<br>
I can see it residing strong and real here in-between the lines on these threads. I can see it in others that have posted here before us as well as in Gary, Tom, John, Art, Ed, Bob, Class Lass and Mom; I saw it in Paul Mahar, aka, Paul PageMaker, whom we have called little PP, Chicken chaser, tunnel rat and a group of other nicknames. <br><br>
Nicknames go with the territory, when you first arrived in Nam if you were lucky, you picked a nickname for yourself but more often then not it was others that picked one out for you. It wasn’t always appreciated, but true to the tag it was often quite appropriate. <br><br>
Why am I saying all this? Because there is a biblical bases for what I am about to post in the post below regarding one of our own. <br><br>
Jesus said; &quot;Greater love has no one than this, that one lay down his life for his friends (John 15:13 NAS).<br>
Many of us who were privileged to go to Nam saw that loved displayed in the real fields of both agony, glory, and honor.  In the Old testament when Jacob whom God trusted and honored was old he gave his blessings to his sons before dying. He called them together and prophesied over them and announced what their inheritance would be. <br><br>
Jacob summoned his sons and said, &quot;Assemble yourselves that I may tell you what shall befall you in the days to come….. in verse eight we read; <br>
&quot;Judah, your brothers shall praise you; your hand shall be on the neck of your enemies; your father's sons shall bow down to you. <br><br>
The name Judah, means; the praise of the Lord; a confession. He is further described in verse nine and ten,<br><br>
&quot;Judah is a lion's whelp; from the prey, my son, you have gone up. He couches, he lies down as a lion, and as a lion, who dares rouse him up? The scepter shall not depart from Judah, nor the ruler's staff from between his feet… <br><br>
A brother that has been posting here has a confession to make, it is posted below, in the Proverbs there is another saying, “Let another praise you, and not your own mouth; a stranger, and not your own lips. (Proverbs 27:2, NAS)<br><br>
Paul Mahar, I am honored to know you because you are the type of individual I would have risked my life in Vietnam to save. You have my respect. <br>
In Nam while you were and I were there on July 19th, 1967, My squad  leader, Marine Corporal Ronald Allen Moore volunteered in my place. Before he left our perimeters wire, he saw me laying there on the ground cold and huddled up trying to stay warm and He took his utility jacket and placed it over me, I awoke to its warmth, but never thanked him for it and regret it till this day. Less then an hour later his squad was ambushed and he was killed, everyday I realize that it could have been me instead.<br><br>
We called each other Bro in Nam (short for brother), it was not a black thing then, it was an honorable name, everyone was called bro, but everyone in our Company knew Ron Moore was “The Bro,” everyone loved him and he loved everyone. <br><br>
Paul I hereby, lay that utility jacket on you, in honor of Bro and I here by call you “The Bro,” because you are. <br><br>

